# Chapter 3 - Designing Good Data Architecture

## Definition
Data architecture is the design of systems to support the evolving
data needs of an enterprise, achieved by flexible and reversible
decisions reached through careful evaluation of trade-offs.

## Two Types of Data Architecture
- Operational - describes WHAT needs to happen (people, processes, business goals)
- Technical - describes HOW it will happen (ingestion, storage, transformation, serving)

## The 9 Principles of Good Data Architecture
1. Choose common components wisely
2. Plan for failure
3. Architect for scalability
4. Architecture is leadership
5. Always be architecting
6. Build loosely coupled systems
7. Make reversible decisions
8. Prioritize security
9. Embrace FinOps

## Key Insight
Good architecture is never finished.
It evolves constantly in response to business needs and new technology.
Always prefer reversible decisions - two-way doors - over one-way doors.

## Types of Data Architecture
- Data Warehouse - structured, formatted data for reporting and analytics
- Data Lake - stores all data structured and unstructured in one place
- Data Lakehouse - combines the best of both warehouse and lake
- Modern Data Stack - cloud-based plug-and-play modular tools
- Data Mesh - decentralised, each domain owns and serves its own data

## Key Terms I Learned
- ETL - Extract Transform Load
- ELT - Extract Load Transform
- ACID - data transaction standards (Atomicity Consistency Isolation Durability)
- FinOps - managing cloud costs like an engineering discipline
- RTO - Recovery Time Objective, how fast must we recover after failure
- RPO - Recovery Point Objective, how much data loss is acceptable
- Loose Coupling - services are independent and communicate through APIs
- Monolith - one large system doing everything, simple to start but hard to scale

## What This Means for Me
I need to understand the trade-offs between different architecture patterns.
At Entelect I will work with data warehouses, data lakes, and modern data stack tools.
Knowing when to use each one, and why, is what separates a good data engineer
from someone who just follows instructions.